This paper deals with the control of flow networks, which involves the coordination of multiple inputs and flows to achieve a desired output. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a distributed controller that exchanges information over a communication network, which could also place it in the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. The paper also deals with the optimization of coordination among the inputs, which could place it in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The use of passivity properties to prove global asymptotic attraction suggests that the paper could also belong to the Signal and Image Processing (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the case studies involve the use of machine learning techniques, which could place the paper in the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
